{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598129"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:32:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:32:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15438"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15438"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.07,0.22,0.49,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8129"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63126"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8129"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48577"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8746"},{"type":"tags","id":"10943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20611"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63126"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gram staining procedure is a key microbiological technique used in the classification of bacteria. Developed by the Danish microbiologist, Hans Christian Gram, a crystal violet dye is applied to the bacteria. Those that retain the dye are called gram-positive bacteria and those where the dye can be washed out are known as gram-negative bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBacterial causes of diarrhoea can be classified by their gram stain characteristics, which helps guide initial empiric antibiotic therapy. The bacteria list below can all cause diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacteria is gram-positive?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Salmonella enterica","Shigella dysenteriae","Campylobacter jejuni","Clostridium perfringens","Escherichia coli"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClostridium perfringens\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-positive, spore-forming anaerobic bacterium that causes food poisoning. It produces an enterotoxin that leads to diarrhoea, typically 8-16 hours after ingestion of contaminated food. The illness is usually self-limiting and resolves within 24 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalmonella enterica\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EShigella dysenteriae\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003ECampylobacter jejuni\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E are all gram-negative bacteria that commonly cause diarrhoeal illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the gram stain characteristics of common diarrhoeal pathogens is important for guiding initial antibiotic choices, as different antibiotics target gram-positive versus gram-negative cell walls.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clostridium perfringens is a gram-positive, spore-forming anaerobic bacterium that causes food poisoning with diarrhoea","Common bacterial causes of diarrhoea including Shigella, Campylobacter, Salmonella, and Escherichia coli are gram-negative organisms"],"references":["Kaiser L, Surawicz CM. Infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. Best Pract Res Clin Gastroenterol. 2012 Oct;26(5):563-71. doi: 10.1016/j.bpg.2012.11.001. PMID: 23384802","Sell J, Dolan B. Common Gastrointestinal Infections. Prim Care. 2018 Sep;45(3):519-532. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.05.008. Epub 2018 Jul 9. PMID: 30115338","Burd EM, Hinrichs BH. Gastrointestinal Infections. Molecular Pathology in Clinical Practice. 2015 May 19:707\u201334. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-19674-9_50. PMCID: PMC7123654","Kotloff KL. Bacterial diarrhoea. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2022 Apr 1;34(2):147-155. doi: 10.1097/MOP.0000000000001107. PMID: 35165210","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48577"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15438"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48577"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T08:57:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T08:58:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8129"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63126"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Reme